        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To explore the dust and gas structure of the disk, we will observe HD 131835 at 880 um continuum and at the J=3-2 line of different CO
isotopologues. Our justification to select Band 7 is the following. In the hybrid disk around HD 21997, we found that both 12CO and 13CO were optically thick, and only the C18O line was optically thin (Kospal et al. 2013). This example shows that for deriving the basic properties of the gas disk and study its origin, we need to measure all CO isotopologues (see also Williams &amp; Best, 2013, arXiv:1312.0151). Although In Band 6, the J=2-1 line of 12CO, 13CO and C18O can be measured in the same setup, both the example of HD 21997, and our LIME modeling of our present target HD 131835 shows that the J=3-2 lines are so much brighter that it would take less telescope time to observe in Band 7 than in Band 6, even though in Band 7 we will need two setups to obtain all three CO isotopologues. Additionally the Band 7 configuration allows us to measure the HCN(4-3) and the HCO+(4-3) lines, which will provide further information on chemistry, excitation, and ionization of the disk.

For the above mentioned reasons, we defined two observational setups 
(Science goals).

Correlator setup: In this setup, we have one 2 GHz-wide TDM
window for the continuum, and three FDM windows for 12CO(3-2),
HCN(4-3). and HCO+(4-3). We will observe the 12CO with a channel
spacing of 244 kHz (0.2 km/s smoothed spectral resolution), 
and the other two lines with 977 kHz. We note that the ~13 km/s wide
line (Fig. 1a) will easily be resolved even by the lowest resolution setting. 

Sensitivity: the total 12CO line flux is 2.7 Jy km/s with a linewidth of 13 km/s. This flux will be distributed in an extended area (Fig. 3.). Based on our simulations using the C34-3 configuration with a spatial resolution of 0.4 arcsec, we expect a peak flux of ~500 mJy per beam per resolution element for the 12CO line. In order to achieve a signal-to-noise ratio of &gt;10 per channel in the line observation, we request a sensitivity of 4 mJy per beam per resolution element for the representative wavelength of the 12CO(3-2) line.

The total continuum flux of HD~131835 at 880um is ~7.2 mJy (see Fig. 2 right). We note that to achieve the best signal-to-noise, we will combine the TDM observations with FDM data (using the line-free channels only) from both setups (see Science Goal2) to compile the final continuum image. This will result in an aggregate continuum sensitivity of 0.034 mJy/beam. Therefore, we expect to detect the 
dust continuum emission from our source with a signal-to-noise ratio of &gt;15 (see Fig. 3).


Imaging: we request a spatial resolution of 0.4 arcsec, thus, the
C34-3 configuration would be ideal for us. According to our models,
the inner diameter of the cold outer dust ring is &gt;0.6 arcsec, thus
can be definitely resolved with this configuration. The maximum
angular scale in this configuration is 5.2 arcsec, significantly
larger than the expected disk size of ~3.2 arcsec, meaning that flux
loss due to the missing short spacings poses no major problem.

Calibration: We will use system-defined calibration.

Bandpass accuracy: not relevant in our case.

Scheduling/time constraints: Our proposal is not time constrained.

Data rate: high in this setup, but we need to observe three lines
whose distances in frequency means that they can only be observed in
three different basebands.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
